<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-018-148  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 018 148.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Dec 11 1989 v15 n24 p92(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technologies ride a fast track into the 1990s. (Issues for the1990s)(Technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis, Dwight B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>High technology companies must constantly develop new products ifthey wish to remain competitive in the industry.andP;  They must alsoconcentrate on improving product quality, reducing the productdevelopment cycle and establishing electronic links with suppliersand customers.andP;  Companies such as IBM, DEC and Intel Corp spendten percent or more on research and development; typically, 85percent of that figure is spent on current product development,and 15 percent is for research and long-term development.andP;  Duringthe 1990s, it is expected that corporate research will focus onhow current technology can be used most effectively.andP;  Thesemiconductor industry will be the center of interest because itis the foundation for all other electronics products and markets.andO;Technological advancement is limited by marketplace demand forcommon standards as well as by the technologies themselves.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic IndustryFuture TechnologiesCompetitionResearch and DevelopmentSemiconductor industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>